{
  "format": "sky",
  "meta": {
    "app": "Sketchy \u2014 Thinking Frameworks Diagram Editor",
    "fileFormat": "The 'diagram' field contains all data. Everything in 'meta' is documentation only \u2014 ignored when loading.",
    "framework": {
      "name": "Current Reality Tree",
      "description": "Map cause-and-effect to find root causes of undesirable effects",
      "edgeSemantics": "Each edge means the source entity causes the target entity"
    },
    "nodeTypes": {
      "entity": "A proposition or observable condition in the diagram"
    },
    "tags": {
      "ude": "Undesirable Effect \u2014 something you want to eliminate"
    },
    "derivedIndicators": "Not stored in the file, computed from graph topology at render time: Root Cause = no incoming edges \u2014 a fundamental driver, Intermediate Effect = has both incoming and outgoing edges",
    "settings": {
      "layoutDirection": "TB = Top-to-Bottom, BT = Bottom-to-Top (direction of causal flow)"
    },
    "junctionSemantics": "When a node has 2+ incoming edges, junctionType determines logic: 'and' = all causes needed together, 'or' = each cause independently sufficient"
  },
  "version": 1,
  "createdAt": "2026-03-28T16:27:49.570Z",
  "diagram": {
    "schemaVersion": 1,
    "id": "e43118a0-e47e-4b04-9325-5bfa95749bf1",
    "name": "Imported Diagram",
    "frameworkId": "crt",
    "settings": {
      "layoutDirection": "BT",
      "showGrid": true
    },
    "nodes": [
      {
        "id": "n1",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 12,
          "y": 140
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Ottoman imperial decline",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Ottoman Empire ruled Palestine for 401 years (1516\u20131917), but entered serious decline from the late 18th century onward (Britannica)\n\u2022 By the 1830s, the Ottomans lost control of Palestine to Egypt's Muhammad Ali Pasha (1832\u20131840) and could only regain it with British help (Palestine Chronicle)\n\u2022 European powers exploited Ottoman weakness through the Capitulations system, granting foreign subjects privileged status and exemptions from local law (Institute for Palestine Studies)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n2",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 12,
          "y": 12
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Weak local governance",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Ottoman Palestine was divided into three administrative districts \u2014 Jerusalem, Nablus, and Acre \u2014 with indirect control and weak centralized governance after the 17th century (Britannica)\n\u2022 Palestinian villages, towns, and cities had significant autonomy to self-govern; this autonomy extended to early European settlers who exploited Ottoman weakness (Palestine Chronicle)\n\u2022 The Ottoman Land Law of 1858 disrupted traditional communal land tenure, enabling notable families and outside investors to acquire large tracts (Palquest Encyclopedia)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n3",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 552,
          "y": 1052
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Rise of Zionist ideology",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Modern political Zionism is conventionally dated to 1882 with the founding of the Hovevei Zion movement; Theodor Herzl published 'Der Judenstaat' in 1896 (CJPME)\n\u2022 The First Zionist Congress convened in Basel, Switzerland in August 1897, establishing the World Zionist Organization (Reform Judaism)\n\u2022 By 1917, the Zionist movement had secured British support through the Balfour Declaration, pledging a Jewish national home in Palestine (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n4",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 272,
          "y": 1052
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "European antisemitism pressures",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Russian pogroms following the 1881 assassination of Czar Alexander II drove mass Jewish emigration; ~2.5 million Jews left Eastern Europe between 1881\u20131914 (Wikipedia \u2013 First Aliyah)\n\u2022 The May Laws of 1882 restricted where Russian Jews could live and work, intensifying economic hardship (Wikipedia \u2013 First Aliyah)\n\u2022 The rise of Nazism in the 1930s drove the Fifth Aliyah of ~250,000 Jews to Palestine (1929\u20131939), as emigration to other destinations was increasingly restricted (NJOP)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n5",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 312,
          "y": 896
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Jewish immigration waves",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 Between 1882 and 1947, approximately 543,000 Jews immigrated to Palestine in five major waves, joining ~24,000 already present (IZA Discussion Paper No. 89)\n\u2022 The First Aliyah (1882\u20131903) brought ~35,000 immigrants; by the Fifth Aliyah (1929\u20131939), ~250,000 arrived (NJOP)\n\u2022 Jewish population in Palestine grew from ~5% of the total in the 1880s to ~30% by 1939 (Palquest Encyclopedia)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n6",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 832,
          "y": 1052
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Arab Palestinian nationalism",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Arab Palestinian nationalism crystallized in the early 20th century, with the first Palestinian nationalist organizations emerging around 1918\u20131920 (Palquest Encyclopedia)\n\u2022 The 1920 Nebi Musa riots and 1921 Jaffa riots were early expressions of Palestinian political identity against both British rule and Zionist immigration (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Arab Higher Committee, established in 1936 under Haj Amin al-Husseini, led the 1936\u20131939 Arab Revolt demanding independence and an end to Jewish immigration (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n7",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 632,
          "y": 880
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Competing nationalist movements",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 Both Jewish and Arab nationalist movements claimed the same territory, creating a zero-sum dynamic from the 1920s onward (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Peel Commission (1937) was the first official body to recommend partition as the solution to the competing claims (Britannica)\n\u2022 By 1947, the Jewish population had grown to ~33% of the total, with 6% of land privately owned by Jews, while Arabs comprised ~67% of the population (Palquest Encyclopedia)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n8",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3682,
          "y": 3264
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "British wartime promises conflict",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The McMahon-Hussein Correspondence (1915\u20131916) promised Arab independence in exchange for revolt against the Ottomans, but its geographic scope was disputed (Britannica)\n\u2022 The secret Sykes-Picot Agreement (May 1916) divided the Arab provinces between British and French spheres, contradicting promises to the Arabs (Palquest Encyclopedia)\n\u2022 The Balfour Declaration (Nov 2, 1917) pledged British support for a Jewish national home, conflicting with both prior commitments (History.com)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n9",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 3264
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Balfour Declaration support",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Issued on November 2, 1917, the Balfour Declaration was a letter from Foreign Secretary Balfour to Lord Rothschild supporting a Jewish national home in Palestine (Britannica)\n\u2022 At the time, Palestine's population was ~90% Arab; the Declaration made no mention of Arab political or national rights (Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 The Declaration was incorporated into the British Mandate charter, approved by the League of Nations on July 24, 1922 (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n10",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 3264
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "British Mandate authority",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The British Mandate for Palestine was formally established in 1920 and approved by the League of Nations in 1922, lasting until May 14, 1948 (Britannica)\n\u2022 Britain governed ~27,000 sq km with a population that grew from ~750,000 in 1922 to ~1.9 million by 1947 (Palquest Encyclopedia)\n\u2022 The Mandate explicitly incorporated the Balfour Declaration, committing Britain to facilitate Jewish immigration while safeguarding Arab rights (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n11",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 3116
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Dual obligations contradiction",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 Britain was simultaneously obligated to facilitate a Jewish national home and protect the rights of the Arab majority \u2014 goals that proved irreconcilable (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1939 White Paper attempted to limit Jewish immigration to 75,000 over five years, angering both sides (Britannica)\n\u2022 Multiple British commissions (Peel 1937, Woodhead 1938, Anglo-American 1946) failed to resolve the contradiction (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n12",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 312,
          "y": 732
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Land ownership disputes",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Jewish land purchases, often from absentee Arab landlords, displaced Palestinian tenant farmers (fellahin); by 1947, Jews owned ~6\u20137% of Mandate Palestine's land (Palquest Encyclopedia)\n\u2022 The Jewish National Fund (est. 1901) purchased ~936,000 dunams of land by 1947, with a policy of exclusive Jewish labor (Institute for Palestine Studies)\n\u2022 Land transfers led to the eviction of entire Palestinian farming communities, fueling resentment and early nationalist mobilization (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n13",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 312,
          "y": 584
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Economic displacement fears",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Zionist labor ideology of 'conquest of labor' displaced Palestinian Arab workers from Jewish-owned farms and enterprises in the 1920s\u20131930s (Palquest Encyclopedia)\n\u2022 Arab unemployment in cities like Jaffa and Haifa rose as the Jewish economic sector grew increasingly self-contained (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1936\u20131939 Arab Revolt was partly driven by economic grievances, including loss of agricultural land and employment opportunities (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n14",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 352,
          "y": 436
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Early communal violence",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The 1920 Nebi Musa riots in Jerusalem left 5 Jews and 4 Arabs dead; the 1921 Jaffa riots killed 47 Jews and 48 Arabs (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1929 Hebron massacre killed 67 Jews and led to the evacuation of the ancient Jewish community there (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1936\u20131939 Arab Revolt resulted in ~5,000 Arab deaths, ~400 Jewish deaths, and ~200 British deaths (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n15",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 352,
          "y": 288
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Entrenched mutual distrust",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 After the 1929 Hebron massacre, the remaining Jewish community was evacuated, deepening communal separation (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Irgun and Lehi (Jewish paramilitary groups) carried out attacks on Arab targets from the late 1930s, intensifying mutual hostility (Britannica)\n\u2022 By the 1940s, segregated communal institutions \u2014 separate schools, economies, and governance structures \u2014 reinforced distrust on both sides (Palquest Encyclopedia)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n16",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 352,
          "y": 140
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Militia formation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Haganah, founded in 1920, became the main Jewish paramilitary force with ~21,000 members by 1947 (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Irgun (est. 1931) and Lehi/Stern Gang (est. 1940) conducted more radical operations, including bombings and assassinations (Britannica)\n\u2022 Arab militias organized under figures like Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni and Fawzi al-Qawuqji's Arab Liberation Army from the 1930s\u20131940s (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n17",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 352,
          "y": 12
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Irregular armed clashes",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Throughout the 1930s\u20131940s, armed clashes between Jewish and Arab militias escalated in frequency and lethality (Britannica)\n\u2022 The King David Hotel bombing (July 22, 1946) by the Irgun killed 91 people, targeting British headquarters (History.com)\n\u2022 By late 1947, after the UN partition vote, full-scale intercommunal warfare erupted across Palestine (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n18",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 2968
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Failed British mediation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Peel Commission (1937) proposed partition but was rejected by Arab leaders; the Woodhead Commission (1938) found partition impractical (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1939 White Paper tried to balance commitments by capping immigration, but was rejected by Zionists and failed to satisfy Arabs (Britannica)\n\u2022 Britain referred the Palestine problem to the United Nations in February 1947, effectively admitting the failure of its mediation efforts (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n19",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 2820
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Partition proposals rejected",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Peel Commission partition plan of 1937 was accepted in principle by some Zionist leaders but unanimously rejected by the Arab Higher Committee (Britannica)\n\u2022 The UN Partition Plan (Resolution 181, Nov 29, 1947) allocated 56% of land to the Jewish state and 43% to the Arab state, despite Jews being ~33% of the population (UN)\n\u2022 Arab states and the Palestinian leadership rejected the UN plan; Jewish leadership accepted it (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n20",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 2820
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "UN partition plan",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 UN General Assembly Resolution 181 was adopted on November 29, 1947, with 33 votes in favor, 13 against, and 10 abstentions (UN)\n\u2022 The plan proposed dividing Palestine into a Jewish state (~56% of land), an Arab state (~43%), and an international zone for Jerusalem (UN)\n\u2022 The plan triggered immediate violence; within days, intercommunal clashes began across Palestine (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n21",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3362,
          "y": 2672
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "1947 civil war escalation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 From November 1947 to May 1948, civil war between Jewish and Arab forces escalated, with ~250,000\u2013350,000 Palestinians displaced before Israel's declaration of independence (IMEU)\n\u2022 The Deir Yassin massacre (April 9, 1948) killed over 100 Palestinians and became a catalyst for mass Palestinian flight (IMEU)\n\u2022 Jewish forces gained military advantage by early 1948, capturing key cities including Haifa, Jaffa, and Tiberias (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n22",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3362,
          "y": 2524
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "1948 regional war",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel declared independence on May 14, 1948; armies from Egypt, Jordan, Syria, Iraq, and Lebanon invaded the next day (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1948 Arab-Israeli War lasted until March 1949 armistice agreements; Israel controlled 78% of Mandate Palestine (Britannica)\n\u2022 An estimated 6,000 Israelis (~1% of population) and over 10,000 Arab combatants died in the war (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n23",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 2376
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Mass Palestinian displacement",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Over 700,000 Palestinian Arabs were expelled or fled during the 1948 war \u2014 approximately half of Mandate Palestine's Arab population (Wikipedia \u2013 1948 Palestinian expulsion)\n\u2022 Between 400 and 600 Palestinian villages were destroyed during and after the war (Wikipedia \u2013 1948 Palestinian expulsion)\n\u2022 Palestinians call this displacement the Nakba ('catastrophe'), commemorated annually on May 15 (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n24",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 2228
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Refugee crisis persistence",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 UNRWA registered 5.9 million Palestinian refugees as of 2023, making it the world's longest-standing refugee crisis (UN News)\n\u2022 Palestinian refugees are concentrated in Jordan (~2.3 million registered), Lebanon, Syria, the West Bank, and Gaza (UNRWA)\n\u2022 UN General Assembly Resolution 194 (Dec 1948) affirmed the right of return, but it has never been implemented (UN)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n25",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3402,
          "y": 2056
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Stateless Palestinian population",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 An estimated 5\u20136 million Palestinians worldwide remain stateless or without full citizenship rights (UNRWA)\n\u2022 Palestinians in Lebanon are barred from ~70 professions and cannot own property in most cases (Human Rights Watch)\n\u2022 The 2024 ICJ advisory opinion found Israel's prolonged occupation illegal and called for an end to settlement activities (ICJ, July 2024)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n26",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 2376
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Unresolved borders",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The 1949 Armistice Agreements established the Green Line but explicitly stated it was not a permanent border (Britannica)\n\u2022 Jordan controlled the West Bank and East Jerusalem (1948\u20131967); Egypt controlled the Gaza Strip (1948\u20131967) (Britannica)\n\u2022 The status of Jerusalem remained unresolved, with Israel declaring it the capital and the international community largely not recognizing this (UN)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n27",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 2228
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Armistice instability",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The 1949 Armistice lines were violated by both sides; Palestinian fedayeen raids from Gaza and Israeli reprisal operations (e.g., Qibya 1953) continued throughout the 1950s (Britannica)\n\u2022 Border skirmishes along the Syrian-Israeli frontier and Egyptian-Israeli border escalated tensions through the 1950s (Britannica)\n\u2022 Egypt's blockade of the Straits of Tiran and the 1956 Suez Crisis demonstrated the fragility of the armistice arrangements (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n28",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 2068
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Recurring interstate wars",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 The 1956 Suez Crisis (Second Arab-Israeli War) saw Israel, Britain, and France attack Egypt; Israel briefly occupied the Sinai (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1967 Six-Day War (June 5\u201310, 1967) resulted in Israel's capture of the West Bank, Gaza, Sinai, and Golan Heights (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 1973 Yom Kippur War saw Egypt and Syria launch surprise attacks; ~2,700 Israelis and ~8,500 Arab soldiers were killed (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n29",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 1896
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "1967 war outcome",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 In June 1967, Israel captured the West Bank, Gaza Strip, Sinai Peninsula, and Golan Heights in just six days (Britannica)\n\u2022 UN Security Council Resolution 242 (Nov 1967) called for Israeli withdrawal from occupied territories in exchange for peace (UN)\n\u2022 The war displaced an additional ~300,000\u2013430,000 Palestinians, many of them already refugees from 1948 (BADIL)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n30",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3122,
          "y": 1736
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Israeli territorial control",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 After 1967, Israel controlled all of historic Palestine plus the Sinai and Golan Heights \u2014 approximately 89,000 sq km of territory (Britannica)\n\u2022 Israel annexed East Jerusalem in 1967 and the Golan Heights in 1981, but neither annexation is recognized internationally (UN)\n\u2022 As of 2025, over 700,000 Israeli settlers live in the West Bank and East Jerusalem combined (Peace Now; B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n31",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2842,
          "y": 1588
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Military occupation system",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The West Bank has been under Israeli military occupation since June 1967 \u2014 over 57 years (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 Palestinians in the occupied territories live under military law while adjacent Israeli settlers live under Israeli civil law \u2014 a dual legal system (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 As of 2024, Israel maintains full military control (Area C) over ~60% of the West Bank, where most settlements are located (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n32",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3162,
          "y": 1588
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Settlement policy adoption",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The first settlement, Kfar Etzion, was re-established in September 1967; settlement policy accelerated under PM Begin after 1977 (Wikipedia \u2013 Israeli settlement timeline)\n\u2022 Settler population grew from ~1,200 in the West Bank in 1972 to over 500,000 (excluding East Jerusalem) by 2024 (Israeli CBS; Peace Now)\n\u2022 The 2024 ICJ advisory opinion ruled that all Israeli settlements in occupied territory are illegal and must be evacuated (ICJ, July 2024)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n33",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3162,
          "y": 1280
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Settlement expansion growth",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 West Bank settler population (excluding East Jerusalem) grew from ~22,800 in 1983 to ~503,000 by end of 2023 (Israeli CBS)\n\u2022 Under Oslo (1993\u20132000), the settler population nearly doubled from ~115,700 to ~203,000, despite agreements to freeze construction (Wikipedia \u2013 Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 In 2024, Israel approved a record number of settlement housing units \u2014 over 12,855 since January (Peace Now)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n34",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3162,
          "y": 1096
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Fragmented Palestinian territories",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Oslo II (1995) divided the West Bank into Areas A (17%), B (23%), and C (60%); Israel retains full control over Area C (Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 The separation barrier, begun in 2002, runs primarily inside the West Bank, further fragmenting Palestinian territory (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 Over 130 settlements and 100+ outposts create non-contiguous Palestinian enclaves, undermining prospects for a viable state (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n35",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2882,
          "y": 1440
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Movement restrictions",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 As of 2022, there were over 600 checkpoints and physical obstacles restricting Palestinian movement in the West Bank (OCHA)\n\u2022 Prior to the Second Intifada, ~500,000 monthly exits from Gaza into Israel were recorded; by 2007\u20132014, the average dropped to ~4,000 (UNICEF)\n\u2022 The separation barrier, at ~712 km, is more than twice the length of the Green Line and encloses major settlement blocs (B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n36",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2882,
          "y": 1280
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Economic stagnation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Palestinian GDP per capita in Gaza was $1,049 in 2020, four times lower than in the West Bank and Jordan (UNRWA)\n\u2022 Unemployment in Gaza stood at 47% overall and 64% for youth in 2021 (UNRWA)\n\u2022 The World Bank estimated the Palestinian economy lost $2.5 billion annually due to Israeli restrictions on movement and access (World Bank)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n37",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2602,
          "y": 1440
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Governance capacity erosion",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The PA controls only ~17% of the West Bank (Area A) while Israel retains full authority over 60% (Area C) (Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 PA revenue depends heavily on customs and tax revenues collected by Israel and transferred under the Paris Protocol (1994); Israel has repeatedly withheld these funds as leverage (Britannica)\n\u2022 Municipal governance capacity is severely limited by Israeli restrictions on construction permits, water access, and infrastructure development in Area C (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n38",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2842,
          "y": 1112
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "First Intifada uprising",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 The First Intifada began on December 9, 1987, as a largely spontaneous popular uprising against 20 years of occupation (Britannica)\n\u2022 Over 1,000 Palestinians and ~160 Israelis were killed during the First Intifada (1987\u20131993) (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 The uprising was characterized by mass protests, strikes, stone-throwing, and civil disobedience, and brought global attention to the occupation (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n39",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2842,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Security crackdown responses",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel responded to the First Intifada with a policy of 'force, might, and beatings' announced by Defense Minister Rabin in 1988 (Britannica)\n\u2022 Over 120,000 Palestinians were detained during the First Intifada; hundreds of homes were demolished as collective punishment (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 Curfews and closures imposed on Palestinian towns restricted daily life and economic activity throughout the late 1980s and early 1990s (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n40",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2032,
          "y": 792
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Oslo framework",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Oslo Accords were signed on September 13, 1993, at the White House, with Rabin, Arafat, and Clinton (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The accords established the Palestinian Authority and created a five-year interim framework, with final status negotiations to follow (Britannica)\n\u2022 Rabin, Peres, and Arafat received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1994 for the agreement (ADL)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n41",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2032,
          "y": 616
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Interim governance ambiguity",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Oslo II (1995) divided the West Bank into Areas A, B, and C, creating a patchwork of jurisdictions with ambiguous authority (Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 The PA was established as an 'interim self-governing arrangement' \u2014 never intended to be permanent \u2014 but persists over 30 years later (IMEU)\n\u2022 The PA exercised limited control over civil matters but had no sovereignty over borders, airspace, or water resources (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n42",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1992,
          "y": 456
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Final status deferral",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Final status issues \u2014 Jerusalem, refugees, borders, settlements, and security \u2014 were deferred to negotiations originally due by 1999 (Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 The Camp David Summit (July 2000) between Barak, Arafat, and Clinton failed to reach agreement on final status (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The Taba Summit (January 2001) came close to a framework but was cut short by Israeli elections (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n43",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1339.8088244561884,
          "y": 399.57101532077695
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Weak enforcement mechanisms",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Oslo Accords contained no binding enforcement mechanisms for Israeli withdrawal or settlement freezes (IMEU)\n\u2022 The UN Security Council's ability to enforce resolutions was consistently blocked by U.S. vetoes \u2014 over 50 vetoes on Israeli-Palestinian issues (BADIL)\n\u2022 No independent monitoring body was established; the U.S. served as the primary mediator but was widely seen as partial to Israel (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n44",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2512,
          "y": 1108
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Continued settlement expansion",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Despite Oslo's implied settlement freeze, the settler population nearly doubled from ~115,700 to ~203,000 between 1993 and 2000 (Wikipedia \u2013 Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 Israel approved record settlement construction during and after the Oslo period, including over 12,855 housing units in 2024 alone (Peace Now)\n\u2022 In March 2024, Israel seized 10 sq km of West Bank land \u2014 the largest seizure since the Oslo Accords (Haaretz)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n45",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2512,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Loss of trust in talks",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Continued settlement expansion during the Oslo period eroded Palestinian trust in the peace process (Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 The assassination of PM Rabin by an Israeli extremist on November 4, 1995, further undermined the process (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 PM Netanyahu (elected 1996) stated he intended to stop Oslo, and conditioned the 1997 Hebron Protocol on minimizing withdrawals (Wikipedia \u2013 Oslo Accords)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n46",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2512,
          "y": 784
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Second Intifada violence",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Second Intifada erupted on September 28, 2000, following Ariel Sharon's visit to the Temple Mount/Haram al-Sharif (Britannica)\n\u2022 Over 3,000 Palestinians and ~1,000 Israelis were killed during the Second Intifada (2000\u20132005) (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 The year 2002 was the bloodiest, with 1,192 Palestinians and 451 Israelis killed (PCBS; B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n47",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2552,
          "y": 616
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Suicide bombings escalation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Between 2000 and 2007, over 140 Palestinian suicide bombings killed approximately 800 Israeli civilians (Britannica)\n\u2022 Hamas and Palestinian Islamic Jihad claimed responsibility for the majority of attacks, often targeting buses and restaurants (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Passover massacre at the Park Hotel in Netanya (March 27, 2002) killed 30 Israelis and triggered Israel's Operation Defensive Shield (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n48",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1752,
          "y": 620
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Israeli military escalation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel launched Operation Defensive Shield in March 2002, the largest military operation in the West Bank since 1967 (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Battle of Jenin (April 2002) involved heavy fighting in the refugee camp; 52 Palestinians and 23 Israeli soldiers were killed (UN)\n\u2022 Israel reoccupied major West Bank cities and reimposed military control over areas previously transferred to the PA (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n49",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2512,
          "y": 456
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Barrier and checkpoints",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Construction of the West Bank separation barrier began in 2002; ~85% of its route runs inside the West Bank, not along the Green Line (B'Tselem)\n\u2022 The barrier is ~712 km long and incorporates major settlement blocs on the Israeli side (OCHA)\n\u2022 The ICJ ruled the barrier illegal in a 2004 advisory opinion (ICJ, July 2004)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n50",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2552,
          "y": 308
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Territorial fragmentation",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 As of 2025, the West Bank is divided into over 165 non-contiguous Palestinian enclaves surrounded by settlements, barriers, and military zones (OCHA)\n\u2022 Area C (60% of the West Bank), where most settlements are located, remains under full Israeli control (Oslo Accords)\n\u2022 The fragmentation has been described by multiple UN reports as incompatible with a viable Palestinian state (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n51",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2431,
          "y": 2524
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Gaza disengagement",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel unilaterally withdrew ~8,000 settlers and military forces from the Gaza Strip in August\u2013September 2005 (Britannica)\n\u2022 The disengagement was ordered by PM Ariel Sharon despite fierce opposition from settler movements and his own party (Britannica)\n\u2022 Israel maintained control of Gaza's airspace, coastline, and border crossings, leading critics to argue the occupation continued (B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n52",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2431,
          "y": 2376
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Hamas electoral victory",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Hamas won the January 2006 Palestinian legislative elections with 74 of 132 seats, defeating the long-dominant Fatah party (Britannica)\n\u2022 The international community (U.S., EU) imposed sanctions on the Hamas-led PA and cut aid, demanding Hamas recognize Israel (Britannica)\n\u2022 The election result surprised observers and reflected widespread Palestinian disillusionment with Fatah's governance and the stalled peace process (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n53",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2431,
          "y": 2228
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Palestinian political split",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 In June 2007, Hamas seized full military control of Gaza following violent clashes with Fatah forces, killing over 100 (Britannica)\n\u2022 The split created two separate Palestinian governing authorities: Hamas in Gaza and Fatah-led PA in the West Bank (Britannica)\n\u2022 Multiple reconciliation attempts (Mecca 2007, Cairo 2011, 2014 Unity Government) have failed to reunify Palestinian governance (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n54",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2431,
          "y": 2064
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Gaza blockade regime",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel imposed a comprehensive land, sea, and air blockade on Gaza in June 2007, following the Hamas takeover (UNICEF)\n\u2022 The UN Secretary-General found the blockade contravenes international humanitarian law by collectively punishing civilians (UNRWA)\n\u2022 As of 2022, 81.5% of Gaza's population lived below the poverty line and 64% were food insecure (UNRWA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n55",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2471,
          "y": 1736
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Humanitarian dependency",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 By 2022, 80% of Gaza's population depended on humanitarian assistance, up from a small fraction before the blockade (UNRWA)\n\u2022 UNRWA food assistance recipients in Gaza surged from 80,000 in 2000 to 1.1 million by 2022 \u2014 a 1,324% increase (UNRWA)\n\u2022 Clean water was unavailable for 95% of Gaza's population; electricity averaged only 11 hours per day as of 2023 (UNRWA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n56",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1407,
          "y": 1882
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Repeated Gaza wars",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Major Gaza conflicts include Operation Cast Lead (2008\u201309), Operation Pillar of Defense (2012), Operation Protective Edge (2014), and the 2023\u2013present war (Britannica)\n\u2022 The 2014 war lasted 50 days and killed over 2,200 Palestinians, including ~1,500 civilians, and 73 Israelis (UN)\n\u2022 The war beginning October 7, 2023 caused unprecedented destruction; by early 2026, tens of thousands of Palestinians were reported killed (UNRWA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n57",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1171,
          "y": 1736
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Rocket attacks on Israel",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Between 2001 and 2023, thousands of rockets and mortars were fired from Gaza into southern Israel by Hamas, Islamic Jihad, and other factions (Britannica)\n\u2022 Israel's Iron Dome system, deployed in 2011, has intercepted an estimated 90% of rockets aimed at populated areas (Britannica)\n\u2022 Rocket fire served as a primary justification for Israeli military operations in Gaza (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n58",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1411,
          "y": 1588
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Airstrikes and ground raids",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel conducted multiple large-scale military operations in Gaza: Cast Lead (2008\u201309), Pillar of Defense (2012), Protective Edge (2014), and the 2023\u2013present war (Britannica)\n\u2022 Operations involved aerial bombardment, naval shelling, and ground incursions into densely populated urban areas (~5,700 people/sq km) (OCHA)\n\u2022 International human rights organizations documented potential violations of international humanitarian law by all parties (HRW; Amnesty International)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n59",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1451,
          "y": 1440
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Civilian casualties",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 In the 2014 Gaza war, over 1,500 Palestinian civilians were killed, including 551 children (UN)\n\u2022 The 2023\u2013present war caused the highest Palestinian civilian casualties since 1948; by early 2026, UNRWA reported tens of thousands killed (UNRWA)\n\u2022 Israeli civilian casualties from the October 7, 2023 Hamas attack included approximately 1,200 people killed (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n60",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1171,
          "y": 1440
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Infrastructure destruction",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The 2014 Gaza war destroyed or severely damaged over 100,000 homes, 73 mosques, and multiple hospitals (UN)\n\u2022 In the 2023\u2013present conflict, the UN estimated over 60% of Gaza's housing stock was damaged or destroyed (OCHA)\n\u2022 Gaza's sole power plant, water treatment facilities, and road networks suffered extensive damage across multiple conflicts (UNICEF)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n61",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1451,
          "y": 1286
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Humanitarian crisis",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 By mid-2025, acute malnutrition among children under five in Gaza more than doubled due to the blockade and war (UNRWA)\n\u2022 The UN warned of famine conditions in parts of Gaza as of early 2025 (OCHA)\n\u2022 Over 86% of Gaza was within the Israeli-militarized zone or under displacement orders by mid-2025 (UNRWA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n62",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1411,
          "y": 1112
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Radicalization dynamics",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Studies show that exposure to violence and loss in conflict settings significantly increases support for extremist groups (Britannica)\n\u2022 Hamas recruitment reportedly surged after each major Israeli military operation in Gaza (Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 Israeli settler violence in the West Bank increased after major escalations, with far-right ideology gaining mainstream political support (B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n63",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1411,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Hardline political shifts",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Hamas won the 2006 elections partly due to Palestinian frustration with Fatah's perceived corruption and failed negotiations (Britannica)\n\u2022 In Israel, right-wing and religious nationalist parties gained increasing power; the 2022 government was described as the most far-right in Israeli history (Britannica)\n\u2022 Support for a two-state solution declined on both sides: from ~70% in the early 2000s to below 35% among both Israelis and Palestinians by 2024 (various polls)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n64",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1712,
          "y": 308
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Peace talks collapse",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "and",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Camp David Summit (July 2000) collapsed without agreement; each side blamed the other for the failure (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The Annapolis Conference (November 2007) set a goal for a peace deal by end of 2008 but failed (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The Kerry-led negotiations (2013\u20132014) broke down in April 2014 after nine months without results (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n65",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1712,
          "y": 160
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "No viable two-state path",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 No substantive Israeli-Palestinian negotiations have taken place since 2014 (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 Over 700,000 settlers in the West Bank and East Jerusalem make territorial compromise increasingly difficult (Peace Now)\n\u2022 The 2024 ICJ advisory opinion declared Israel's occupation illegal and called for its end, but enforcement mechanisms remain absent (ICJ, July 2024)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n66",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3032,
          "y": 160
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "West Bank instability",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 In 2024, settler attacks on Palestinian communities in the West Bank increased sharply, with over 1,000 incidents recorded (OCHA)\n\u2022 Between October 2023 and December 2025, over 1,000 Palestinians were killed in the West Bank, including 225+ children (UNRWA)\n\u2022 Israel conducted near-daily military raids in northern West Bank cities including Jenin, Tulkarm, and Nablus (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n67",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3312,
          "y": 308
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Settler-Palestinian violence",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 OCHA documented over 1,000 settler-related incidents in the West Bank in 2024, including physical assaults, property destruction, and land seizures (OCHA)\n\u2022 The U.S. imposed sanctions on a small number of Israeli settlers and settlement entities in 2024 for violent acts (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 B'Tselem reported that Israeli military forces frequently failed to intervene in settler attacks or actively participated alongside settlers (B'Tselem)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n68",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3032,
          "y": 308
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Weak PA legitimacy",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The PA has not held elections since 2006; President Abbas's term officially expired in 2009 (Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 Polls consistently show majority Palestinian dissatisfaction with the PA; a 2023 survey found ~80% wanted Abbas to resign (Palestinian Center for Policy and Survey Research)\n\u2022 PA security coordination with Israel, involving arrest of Palestinian militants, is deeply unpopular and seen as collaboration (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n69",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 3032,
          "y": 456
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Security coordination tensions",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 PA security forces cooperate with Israeli forces under Oslo arrangements to arrest suspected militants in the West Bank (Britannica)\n\u2022 This cooperation is widely condemned by Palestinians and has contributed to declining PA legitimacy (Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 Despite security coordination, Israel regularly conducts independent military raids in PA-controlled areas (Area A), undermining PA authority (OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n70",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1432,
          "y": 160
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Periodic escalation cycles",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 A cycle of escalation-ceasefire-escalation has characterized Gaza conflicts since 2008, with major operations in 2008\u201309, 2012, 2014, 2021, 2022, and 2023\u2013present (Britannica)\n\u2022 The West Bank has experienced periodic 'knife intifadas' and escalation cycles, particularly in 2015\u20132016 and from 2023 onward (OCHA)\n\u2022 Each cycle of violence has deepened mistrust and moved both populations further from compromise (various polls)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n71",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1360,
          "y": 604
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "International diplomatic paralysis",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The U.S. has vetoed over 50 UN Security Council resolutions critical of Israel since 1972 (BADIL)\n\u2022 The Middle East Quartet (U.S., EU, Russia, UN), formed in 2002, has produced roadmaps and statements but no breakthrough (Britannica)\n\u2022 Other international initiatives \u2014 the Arab Peace Initiative (2002), the Geneva Accord (2003) \u2014 have been largely ignored by the parties (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n72",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1131,
          "y": 2228
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Regional proxy dynamics",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Iran has provided financial and military support to Hamas and Palestinian Islamic Jihad since the 1990s (Britannica)\n\u2022 Hezbollah in Lebanon, backed by Iran, has fought Israel in 2006 and engaged in cross-border hostilities during the 2023\u2013present Gaza war (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Abraham Accords (2020) normalized relations between Israel and UAE, Bahrain, Morocco, and Sudan, reshaping regional dynamics (U.S. State Dept.)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n73",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1131,
          "y": 2068
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "External funding of militants",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Iran reportedly provides Hamas with an estimated $100 million annually in funding, along with weapons technology and training (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 Hezbollah has supplied rockets and military training to Palestinian factions in Gaza (Britannica)\n\u2022 Qatar has provided hundreds of millions of dollars to Gaza, ostensibly for humanitarian purposes, with Israeli approval at times (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n74",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1131,
          "y": 1884
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Militant capability persistence",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Despite multiple Israeli operations, Hamas has maintained a significant arsenal; it was estimated to possess 10,000\u201320,000 rockets before October 2023 (Britannica)\n\u2022 The tunnel network in Gaza extended for hundreds of kilometers and served as military infrastructure (Britannica)\n\u2022 Hamas demonstrated sophisticated operational capability in the October 7, 2023 attack, which involved ~3,000 fighters breaching the Gaza barrier (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n75",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1491,
          "y": 776
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Israeli security-first doctrine",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel's security doctrine has prioritized military deterrence and preemptive action since its founding in 1948 (Britannica)\n\u2022 Annual Israeli defense spending exceeds $24 billion, representing ~5.5% of GDP \u2014 among the highest ratios globally (SIPRI)\n\u2022 The Iron Dome, David's Sling, and Arrow missile defense systems represent layered defense investments (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n76",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1171,
          "y": 1268
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Collective punishment perceptions",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Israel's policy of home demolitions \u2014 over 100,000 Palestinian homes demolished since 1948 (not counting Gaza wars) \u2014 is widely characterized as collective punishment (BADIL; Al Jazeera)\n\u2022 Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch have documented systematic discriminatory practices against Palestinian civilians under occupation (HRW; Amnesty)\n\u2022 Three major international human rights organizations (Amnesty, HRW, B'Tselem) concluded that Israel practices apartheid in the occupied territories (Amnesty 2022; HRW 2021; B'Tselem 2021)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n77",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1092,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Global polarization narratives",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The Israeli-Palestinian conflict generates intense polarization globally; UN General Assembly resolutions on Palestine regularly pass with 150+ votes in favor (UN)\n\u2022 Social media has amplified competing narratives; protests during the 2023\u2013present war drew millions worldwide on both sides (various media)\n\u2022 University campus protests over the conflict led to institutional and political debates in the U.S., Europe, and globally in 2024 (various media)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n78",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1152,
          "y": 794
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Reduced compromise incentives",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 Hardline political forces on both sides benefit electorally from confrontation rather than compromise (various polls)\n\u2022 The Netanyahu coalition's dependence on settler-movement parties (Religious Zionism, Jewish Power) incentivizes settlement expansion over negotiations (Britannica)\n\u2022 Hamas's political model is based on resistance rather than negotiation, creating a mutual reinforcement of hardline positions (Al Jazeera)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n79",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1152,
          "y": 160
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Entrenched status quo bias",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 No substantive peace negotiations have occurred since 2014, the longest gap since Oslo began in 1993 (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The status quo \u2014 continued occupation, settlement expansion, and periodic military operations \u2014 has become self-reinforcing (OCHA)\n\u2022 International mediation efforts have stalled as the U.S. has become increasingly polarized on the issue and other global crises compete for attention (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n80",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1688,
          "y": 12
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "No durable peace",
          "tags": [
            "ude"
          ],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The conflict has persisted for over 100 years (since the early 1920s) without a durable peace agreement (Britannica)\n\u2022 The Oslo process, designed as a five-year interim arrangement in 1993, remains the last significant framework \u2014 over 30 years later, without final status resolution (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 As of 2026, the situation is characterized by ongoing war in Gaza, rising West Bank violence, deepening occupation, and no active peace process (UNRWA; OCHA)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n81",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2172,
          "y": 1096
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "US strategic alliance",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The U.S.-Israel strategic alliance has been a cornerstone of U.S. Middle East policy since the 1960s (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 The U.S. provides Israel with $3.8 billion annually in military aid under the 2016 Memorandum of Understanding (10-year, $38 billion total) (Congressional Research Service)\n\u2022 Israel is the largest cumulative recipient of U.S. foreign aid since WWII, receiving over $300 billion (adjusted for inflation) (Congressional Research Service)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n82",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2232,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "US military aid to Israel",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The U.S. provides $3.8 billion annually in Foreign Military Financing to Israel under the 2016\u20132026 MOU (Congressional Research Service)\n\u2022 U.S. military aid includes advanced fighter jets (F-35s), missile defense funding (Iron Dome, David's Sling), and precision munitions (Congressional Research Service)\n\u2022 Additional emergency military aid packages were approved during the 2023\u2013present war (Congressional Research Service)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n83",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1952,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "US-led peace process",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The U.S. has been the primary mediator in Israeli-Palestinian peace efforts since the 1970s, including Camp David (1978, 2000), Madrid (1991), Oslo (1993), and Annapolis (2007) (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 Critics argue the U.S. role as both Israel's chief ally and primary mediator creates an inherent conflict of interest (various analysts)\n\u2022 The Trump administration's 'Peace to Prosperity' plan (January 2020) was rejected by Palestinians as heavily pro-Israel (Britannica)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n84",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 1672,
          "y": 948
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "US UN diplomatic shielding",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 The U.S. has vetoed over 50 UN Security Council resolutions critical of Israel since 1972, shielding it from binding international action (various sources)\n\u2022 In December 2016, the Obama administration abstained on UNSC Resolution 2334 condemning settlements \u2014 a rare exception (UN)\n\u2022 This diplomatic protection has been cited as a major factor in international paralysis on the conflict (various analysts)"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n85",
        "type": "entity",
        "position": {
          "x": 2472,
          "y": 1268
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Weak US conditionality",
          "tags": [],
          "junctionType": "or",
          "notes": "\u2022 U.S. military aid to Israel has never been conditioned on settlement freezes or compliance with international law in a binding way (Congressional Research Service)\n\u2022 The Leahy Law, which prohibits U.S. military aid to units that commit human rights violations, has rarely been applied to Israel (U.S. State Dept.)\n\u2022 Bipartisan U.S. political support for Israel has historically precluded serious conditionality on aid (Congressional Research Service)"
        }
      }
    ],
